[2] WHO Ebola response roadmap -- Situation report
Date: 26 Nov 2014
Source: WHO [excerpted, edited]
http://who.int/csr/disease/ebola/situation-reports/en


A total of 15 935 confirmed, probable, and suspected cases of Ebola virus disease (EVD) have been reported in 6 affected countries (Guinea, Liberia, Mali, Sierra Leone, Spain and the United States of America) and 2 previously affected countries (Nigeria and Senegal) up to the end of 23 Nov [2014]. There have been 5689 reported deaths.

Cases and deaths continue to be under-reported in this outbreak. Reported case incidence is stable in Guinea (148 confirmed cases reported in the week to 23 Nov 2014), stable or declining in Liberia (67 new confirmed cases in the week to 23 Nov 2014), and may still be rising in Sierra Leone (385 new confirmed cases in the week to 23 Nov 2014).

The total number of cases reported in Sierra Leone since the outbreak began will soon eclipse the number reported from Liberia. The case fatality rate [CFR] across the 3 most-affected countries in patients with a recorded definitive outcome is approximately 60 percent; 3 health-care workers were reported infected with EVD in Guinea in the week to 23 Nov 2014.

Response activities continue to intensify in line with the UNMEER aim to isolate 70 percent of EVD cases and safely bury 70 percent of EVD-related deaths by 1 Dec 2014. Guinea isolates over 70 percent of all reported cases of EVD, and has more than 80 percent of required safe burial teams. Progress on isolation and safe burials has apparently been slower in parts of Liberia and Sierra Leone, although uncertainties in data preclude firm conclusions. At a national level, both countries are apparently unable to isolate 70 percent of patients, although data on isolation is up to 3 weeks out of date.

Every EVD-affected district in the 3 intense-transmission countries has access to a laboratory for case confirmation within 24 hours of sample collection. All 3 countries report that more than 80 percent of registered contacts associated with known cases of EVD are traced, though the low mean number of contacts registered per case suggests that contact tracing is still a challenge in areas of intense transmission... - more

